An '''Alternate Reconstitutional Base''' ('''ARB''') is a concept used during the [[Cold War]] by the [[United States Air Force]]'s [[Strategic Air Command]] for the rearming of nuclear bombers. The idea was, after a nuclear exchange, primary [[Strategic Air Command|SAC]] airfields would be destroyed and returning bombers would have no location to rearm their stores and reattack additional targets. ARB allowed trained teams to depart their home installation and create landing locations for returning bombers.<ref>[http://www.airforcehistoryindex.org/data/001/047/464.xml Air Force Historical Research Agency IRIS Document 01047464]</ref><ref>[http://www.airforcehistoryindex.org/data/001/041/159.xml Air Force Historical Research Agency IRIS Document 01041159]</ref><ref>[http://www.airforcehistoryindex.org/data/001/033/516.xml Air Force Historical Research Agency IRIS Document 01033516]</ref><ref>[http://www.airforcehistoryindex.org/data/001/031/378.xml Air Force Historical Research Agency IRIS Document 01031378]</ref><ref>[http://www.airforcehistoryindex.org/data/000/456/970.xml Air Force Historical Research Agency IRIS Document 00456970]</ref>
==Civilian Airfields== A few civilian airfields, such as [[Clinton-Sherman Airport]], were originally [[Strategic Air Command|SAC]] bases. The long-length runways were maintained, as well as the [[Christmas tree (aviation)|Christmas tree]] alert structure for possible reuse by [[Strategic Air Command|SAC]] forces in the event of nuclear war.
==Training== Various SAC communications squadrons would conduct ARB training by installing a mobile [[high frequency]] radio set at a pre-planned site and establish a communications net.
==See also== *[[Post Attack Command and Control System]] *[[Headquarters Emergency Relocation Team]] *[[55th Mobile Command and Control Squadron]]
