{{EngvarB|date=July 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}} [[File:Arthur Beale.jpg|thumb|right]] '''Arthur Beale''' is a [[yacht-chandler]] on London's [[Shaftesbury Avenue]], which stocks a wide variety of nautical equipment and accessories. The business started as the [[rope-maker]] '''John Buckingham''' by the nearby [[Fleet river]] in the 16th century and has been based in premises in [[Bloomsbury]] since then. In the 19th century, they became known as the exclusive suppliers of climbing rope to the [[Alpine Club (UK)|Alpine Club]]. They still make and stock a large variety of ropes and lines and so also supply [[theatrical rigging]] and ornamental ropes for decoration and crowd control.
==History== [[File:John Buckingham.png|thumb|right|Advert in ''[[Edward Whymper|Whymper's Guides Advertiser]]'' in 1897]] The business started as rope-maker, John Buckingham, on the [[Fleet river]] at the start of the 16th century.<ref>{{citation |page=832 |title=The London Encyclopedia |year=2008 |isbn=9781405049245}}</ref> In the early 19th century, they had premises at number 6 in the Middle Row of [[St Giles, London|St Giles]]—an impressive terrace in the middle of [[Broad Street (ward)|Broad Street]]—but had to move when this was demolished in 1843.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/bloomsbury-project/streets/middle_row_bloomsbury.htm |work=UCL Bloomsbury Project |title=Middle Row Bloomsbury |date= 14 April 2011 |author=Deborah Colville}}</ref>
They then operated from premises on Shaftesbury Avenue when John Buckingham and then the new proprietor, Arthur Beale, were exclusive suppliers of [[climbing rope]] to early members of the [[Alpine Club (UK)|Alpine Club]].<ref name=CM/> This was made to the club's specification so that it was both light and strong, being made from three strands of [[manila hemp]], treated to be rot proof and marked with a red thread of [[worsted]] yarn.<ref name=CM>{{citation |page=58|author=George Dixon Abraham |title=The Complete Mountaineer |year=1908}}</ref> This rope was used for British expeditions to [[Mount Everest]] and [[Antarctica]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.arthurbeale.co.uk/newsletter_140618.pdf |title=Arthur Beale Summer Watch |year=2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140711205117/http://www.arthurbeale.co.uk/newsletter_140618.pdf |archivedate=11 July 2014 }}</ref> It also supplied [[ice axe]]s to polar explorer, [[Ernest Shackleton]]; the [[flagpole]] for [[Buckingham Palace]] and rigging for [[escapologist]]s and the [[window display]]s of [[Selfridges]] department store.<ref name=DT>{{citation |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/the-filter/best-of-british-arthur-beale-chandlery/ |title=Best of British: Arthur Beale Chandlery |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=31 March 2016 |author=Christian House}}</ref>
[[File:Monkey's fist.jpg|thumb|right|a [[monkey's fist]] with an [[eye splice]], custom-made at Arthur Beale]] The business now trades mainly as a [[yacht]] chandler, stocking and supplying nautical equipment such as a [[monkey's fist]] – a weighted ball of rope used for line-throwing.<ref>{{citation |pages=90&ndash;91 |chapter=The Shops That Time Forgot |title=Ben Le Vay's Eccentric London: A Practical Guide to a Curious City |author=Benedict Le Vay |isbn=9781841623948 |year=2012}}</ref> To support the retailing, they have a workshop downstairs, where they produce special orders for ropes and rigging.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.timeout.com/london/shopping/ye-olde-shoppes-3 |title=Still Open: The Guide to Traditional London Shops |author=Sally Venables, Steve Williams |isbn=978-1904772446 |year=2006}}</ref> This business was declining but, in 2014, veteran sailor and theatrical chandler, Alasdair Flint, took over with business partner Gerry Jeatt and plans to revive it.<ref>{{citation |url=http://intheboatshed.net/2014/07/04/tilman-medal-winner-alasdair-flint-business-partner-gerry-jeatt-rescue-historic-london-chandlers-arthur-beale/ |title=Tilman medal winner Alasdair Flint and business partner Gerry Jeatt rescue historic London chandlers Arthur Beale |author=Gavin Atkin |date=4 July 2014 |work=In the Boat Shed}}</ref>
==Reviews== Eugenia Bell, writing in ''The Traditional Shops and Restaurants of London'', praised the establishment:<ref>{{citation |title=The Traditional Shops and Restaurants of London |page=193 |chapter=Arthur Beale |isbn=1-892145-95-2 |year=2010 |author=Eugenia Bell}}</ref>{{quote|The teal shopfront matches the pegboards inside, festooned with gleaming brass shackles, bolts and hooks of every size and description. Spools of ropes adorn all sides of the store and rigging is still assembled in a downstairs workshop. Beale's is a stunning shop, as much for its incongruity as for its dazzling display.}}
In 1999, ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' likewise commented on their incongruity but praised the range of nautical equipment:<ref>{{citation |publisher=Time Out |date=30 November 1999 |title=Arthur Beale |url=http://www.timeout.com/london/shopping/arthur-beale}}</ref>{{quote|There are some odd shops in London, but few beat the surprise factor of finding a yacht chandler in Shaftesbury Avenue. Arthur Beale is a retail survivor, hanging on long after many of the other chandlers went bust. It may look old-fashioned – and it stubbornly holds out against this new-fangled internet thing – but the stock is as useful now as it ever was for sailors.}}
