{{1r|date=March 2018}} [[File:Dalen fyr 2007 l.jpg|thumb|AGA light near [[Djurgården]] in Stockholm]]
A '''Dalén light''' is a [[light]] produced from burning of [[carbide gas]] (acetylene), combined with a solar sensor which automatically operates the light only during darkness.
==Overview== The technology was the predominant form of light source in [[lighthouses]] from the 1900s through the 1960s, when electric lighting had become dominant. The system was invented by [[Gustaf Dalén]] and marketed by his company [[AGA AB|AGA]]. Dalén later invented the [[AGA cooker]] in 1922. The Dalén light is notable because of its [[sun valve]] (a.k.a. solar valve), which earned its inventor the [[Nobel prize in physics]]. The [[Carbide lamp]] was developed in the early 1900s. While the lamps proved useful in many applications, the problem of safely storing [[acetylene]] meant they needed regular refilling which constrained their use in applications such as lighthouses.
==Examples== Lighthouses using Dalén lighting have included: *[[Barrenjoey, New South Wales|Barrenjoey Lighthouse, New South Wales]] (1932–1972) *[[Peninsula Point Light]] (1922–1936) [[Upper Peninsula]] [[Michigan]] United States *[[Point Stephens Light]], [[New South Wales]] (1922–1960) *[[Punta Sur|Celarain]] Lighthouse, Mexico (1934 – ) *[[Skerryvore]] Lighthouse, the [[Hebrides]] ( –1959) *[[Recalada a Bahía Blanca Light]], [[Argentina]] (1928–1974)<ref name=Centennial>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hidro.gov.ar/noticias/FaroRecaladaBBca.asp |title=Centenario del Faro Recalada a Bahía Blanca |trans-title=Centennial to Recalada a Bahía Blanca Lighthouse |work=hidro.gov.ar |accessdate=11 August 2010 |language=Spanish |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706084426/http://www.hidro.gov.ar/noticias/FaroRecaladaBBca.asp |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df= }}</ref>
