__NOTOC__ [[File:NNPTC_Goose_Creek.JPG|thumb|250px|Naval Nuclear Power Training Command Nuclear Power School]] A '''Moored training ship (MTS)''' is a [[United States Navy]] designation for [[Nuclear submarine|nuclear powered]] [[submarine]]s that have been converted to [[training ship]]s for the [[Naval Nuclear Power Training Command]]'s [[Nuclear_Power_School#Nuclear_Power_Training_Unit|Nuclear Power Training Unit (NPTU)]] at [[Naval Support Activity Charleston]] in [[South Carolina]]. The NPTU is part of the Navy's [[Nuclear Power School]] at [[Goose Creek, South Carolina|Goose Creek, S.C.]]. The Navy uses decommissioned nuclear submarines and converts them to MTSs to train personnel in the operation and maintenance of submarines and their nuclear reactors. The first moored training ship was {{USS|Sam Rayburn|SSBN-635}} a {{sclass-|James Madison|submarine|0}} [[fleet ballistic missile submarine]], redesignated as (MTS-635) in 1989, followed a year later by {{USS|Daniel Webster|SSBN-626}}, a {{sclass-|Lafayette|submarine|0}} [[ballistic missile]] submarine, redesignated as (MTS-626). Conversion of these two boats took place at the [[Charleston Naval Shipyard]] and modifications included special mooring arrangements with a mechanism to absorb power generated by the main propulsion shaft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/systems/ship/mts.htm|title=MTS|publisher=globalsecurity.org|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref>
The Navy plans to add two more moored training ships to this facility, {{USS|La Jolla|SSN-701}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nvr.navy.mil/SHIPDETAILS/SHIPSDETAIL_SSN_701_2195.HTML|title=SSN-701|publisher=nvr.navy.mil|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> and {{USS|San Francisco|SSN-711}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nvr.navy.mil/SHIPDETAILS/SHIPSDETAIL_SSN_711_2205.HTML|title=SSN-711|publisher=nvr.navy.mil|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> a pair of {{sclass-|Los Angeles|submarine|0}} [[attack submarines]]. The conversions for these two will take place at the [[Norfolk Naval Shipyard]]<ref name="MTS">{{cite web|url=https://www.naval-technology.com/news/us-navys-norfolk-shipyard-undocks-uss-la-jolla-submarine/|title=US Navy's Norfolk shipyard undocks USS ''La Jolla'' submarine|publisher=naval-technology.com|date=6 December 2017|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> and they will then be taken to NSA Charleston. ''La Jolla'' became inactive in early 2015 and began the 32 month conversion to a training ship. Changes include having the hull cut into three sections, with the center section being recycled and the other two joined with three new sections, manufactured by [[Electric Boat]], extending the length on the boat by 23 m (76 ft). The project is expected to be completed by the end of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://navaltoday.com/2017/12/01/uss-la-jolla-reaches-moored-training-ship-conversion-milestone/|title=USS ''La Jolla'' reaches moored training ship conversion milestone|publisher=navaltoday.com|date=1 December 2017|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> ''San Francisco'' arrived at Norfolk to begin her conversion in January 2018<ref name=MTS />
